Question 1

Load in the nyc_bikes data from the tsibbledata package. Have an initial look at it to see what youre working with. Create three new columns: one that stores only the year the bike was used, one that stores only the month the bike was used, and one that stores the date. Use the data stored in start_time to create these new columns.

nyc_bikes %>% 
  select(start_time)
nyc_bikes <- nyc_bikes %>%
  mutate(year_of_use = year(start_time)) %>% 
  mutate(month_of_use =month(start_time)) %>% 
  mutate(date_of_use = date(start_time)
         )

Question 4

Lets begin to build a model. For this, we will use the downsampled by date dataset we created above in question 3.

nyc_bikes_by_date <- nyc_bikes %>% 
  index_by(date_of_use)  %>% 
  summarise(count = n())

Lets begin to build a model. For this, we will test the NAIVE, MEAN, and SNAIVE model.

nyc_bikes_filled <- nyc_bikes_by_date %>%
  tsibble::fill_gaps(count = as.integer(median(count)))

nyc_bikes_filled
fit <- nyc_bikes_filled %>% 
  model(
    naive = NAIVE(date),
    mean_model = MEAN(date),
    snaive = SNAIVE(date)
  
        )

However, the first thing youll notice when you try and build a model is that you get an error: >.data contains implicit gaps in time. You should check your data and convert implicit gaps into explicit missing values using tsibble::fill_gaps() if required. First, create a new tibble which uses the fill_gaps() function to fill in missing values. You havent come across this in class, but you should be able to look it up and use it using the help. Think about what value you might want to fill the missing values with. Justify your choice.
Hint: think back to our missing values lesson. Do you want to leave them blank? Or do you want to impute each day with the median, last observation carried forward, etc.

Question 6

Test your model accuracy : -choose a training data set from your main dataset, -build a forecast on the training set, and then -plot the training set forecast against the real data. -Calculate model accuracy.

Train - test 75%:25% total range is jan18-jan19 therefore train jan18-sep18 train and oct18-dec18 test

Training set from  2018-01-01 to 2018-09-30
train <- nyc_bikes_filled %>% 
  filter_index("1992 Q1" ~ "2006 Q4")

fit_train <- train %>% 
  model(
    mean_model = MEAN(Beer),
    arima = ARIMA(Beer),
    snaive = SNAIVE(Beer)
  )
